      <div class="row-fluid">
        <p>Evan Kawahara was once but a man. Borne of poor rice farmers on the island of Honshu, Japan, he spent his youth rapping (before it was cool) and flirting with the village girls. Banished as a teenager for seducing the village patriarch's daughter, he journeyed around the world, punching things and impregnating women before settling in Berkeley, California. After serving a 400 year tenure as Dean of Gender & Women's Studies, he suddenly disappeared without a word. Sightings continued for years, until he was finally seen leaping off Mount Fuji, exploding into a brilliant supernova. From that moment onward, the world was inexplicably different... as if some balance had been restored. Historians have tried to document Kawahara's life; their attempts can be found <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZG_AZQJgz8w">here</a> and <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sbRom1Rz8OA">here</a>. His final mortal contribution to Earth was a website for indie movie professionals to connect and find each other.</p>
        <p> Now, in the end, one must realize that Evan is no longer just a man, but a culmination of the human spirit. "He" is the profound mixture of our hopes, dreams, desires, and emotions: our greatest ambitions, our most righteous goods, and our most wicked evils. Look deep inside yourself. Buried under your consciousness, Kawahara is there. He's probably also your father.</p>
